            department = "Microlab",
            section = "Identification",
            objective = "To detail the gram-staining protocol to differentiate gram-positive and gram-negative bacterial strains isolated from cleanrooms.",
            scope = "All bacterial isolates retrieved during environmental monitoring or sterility testing.",
            responsibility = "Microbiologist executes. Lab Supervisor reviews.",
            procedure = "Prepare a clean glass slide. Place a small drop of sterile water on the slide. Emulsify a single colony to make a thin smear.;Allow the smear to air dry completely. Heat-fix the slide by passing it through a Bunsen burner flame three times.;Flood the slide with Crystal Violet solution (primary stain) for 1 minute. Rinse gently with water.;Flood with Gram's Iodine solution (mordant) for 1 minute. Rinse with water. This forms crystal violet-iodine complexes inside the cells.;Decolorize with 95% Ethanol dropwise for 10-20 seconds. Rinse immediately with water to stop decolorization.;Counterstain with Safranin solution for 30 seconds. Rinse with water, blot dry with lens paper, and observe under light microscope (100x oil immersion).;Identify cell morphology and color: Gram-positive appear purple/blue; Gram-negative appear pink/red.",
            safetyPrecautions = "Wear safety glasses and gloves when handling staining dyes and chemical decolorizing reagents.",
